French President Macron and U.S. President Biden held a meeting at Villa Bonaparte in Rome. Macron expressed the importance of the discussions in clarifying European sovereignty and defense, as well as strengthening the cooperation between NATO and the European Union. They also discussed cooperation in the Indo-Pacific region, counterterrorism efforts, and bilateral partnerships in various sectors such as armament exports, nuclear energy, and technology. Both leaders emphasized the value of the Franco-American alliance and their commitment to each other. Biden acknowledged that the handling of the AUKUS issue was clumsy and expressed his desire to repair and strengthen the relationship with France. Macron stated that they had clarified many things and emphasized the need for stronger coordination and cooperation in the future. They also discussed concrete actions to strengthen their partnership in the Sahel region.